-- Germany's DAX Closes Little Changed, Posts Third Weekly Gain; VW Advances
-- B y   J u l i e   C r u z
-- 2010-10-22T15:56:19Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-22/dax-falls-ahead-of-business-confidence-report-henkel-man-se-shares-drop.html
German stocks closed little changed,
with the benchmark DAX Index posting a third weekly gain, after
the gauge rose to the highest level since June 2008 yesterday.  HeidelbergCement AG and Bayer AG led declining shares.
Volkswagen AG rose 3.2 percent as Europe’s largest carmaker said
nine-month profit jumped more than sixfold, beating analysts’
estimates.  Fuchs Petrolub AG  climbed after reporting an increase
in profit.  The benchmark DAX Index slipped 0.1 percent to 6,605.84 at
the 5.30 p.m. close in Frankfurt, posting a weekly gain of 1.8
percent. The measure has rallied 6.1 percent this month amid
speculation policy makers at the U.S. Federal Reserve will
announce another round of asset purchases at their November
meeting in a bid to jumpstart economic growth. The broader  HDAX
Index  was also little changed today.  “We expect the DAX to climb steadily and reach our 6,900
target at the end of the year,”  Andreas Huerkamp , a Frankfurt-
based strategist at Commerzbank AG, wrote in a report today.
“The DAX is going through a relatively normal recovery after a
recession.”  A report today showed the country’s business confidence
unexpectedly climbed in October to the highest level in three
and a half years. The Munich-based Ifo institute said its
business climate index, based on a survey of 7,000 executives,
rose to 107.6 from 106.8 in September. That’s the highest since
May 2007. Economists had expected a drop to 106.5, according to
the median of 38 forecasts in Bloomberg News survey.  HeidelbergCement, VW  HeidelbergCement, the world’s largest maker of aggregates
used to produce concrete and asphalt, dropped 1 percent to 36.62
euros, the first retreat in four trading sessions.  Bayer ,
Germany’s biggest drugmaker, slipped 0.9 percent to 54.90 euros.  Volkswagen preferred shares  surged 3.2 percent to 96.76
euros. Net income was 4 billion euros, compared with 655 million
euros a year earlier, Wolfsburg, Germany-based VW said today.
Analysts predicted profit of 2.8 billion euros, the average of
four estimates compiled by Bloomberg. Sales gained 20 percent to
92.5 billion euros. VW didn’t break out third-quarter figures.  Fuchs Petrolub preferred shares advanced 1.1 percent to
93.20 euros. Germany’s largest maker of lubricants said nine-
month profit after tax rose to 132.7 million euros from 81.8
million euros.  Wincor Nixdorf AG climbed 2.6 percent to 51.67 euros as
Berenberg Bank lifted its recommendation on the world’s second-
largest maker of automated teller machines to “buy” from
“hold.”  -- Editors:  Jason Carey ,  David Merritt .  To contact the reporters on this story:
